#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:3 856a67a1d67945889ad20ded85cefb5f
msgid "Issue tracking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:6 2ae9b7bd06114ff99bb8814a55762e52
msgid ""
"We use `GitHub Issues <https://docs.github.com/en/issues>`__ as our "
"`issue tracking system "
"<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Issue_tracking_system>`__. All issues "
"pertaining to the Qubes OS Project (including auxiliary infrastructure "
"such as this website) are tracked in `qubes-issues "
"<https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/issues>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:9 d56f6476a87647d48290999463a03866
msgid "How to open a new issue"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:12 49857ede9971418d83c803e842034afb
msgid "First, let’s make sure the issue tracker is the right place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:15 51a958870b534af280a56ac09c5024c7
msgid "I need help, have a question, or want to discuss something."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:18 57b4ac541f7949af889500b5bfb1ae8a
msgid ""
"We’re happy to help, answer questions, and have discussions, but the "
"issue tracker is not the right place for these activities. Instead, "
"please see :doc:`Help, Support, Mailing Lists, and Forum "
"</introduction/support>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:21 4252f9feefd1493489975047f9bc35c0
msgid "I see something that should be changed in the documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:24 dcdcd766da134e6e967dbf8a2b93cc0c
msgid ""
"We encourage you to submit the change yourself! Please see the :doc:`how "
"to edit the documentation </developer/general/how-to-edit-the-rst-"
"documentation>` for instructions on how to do so. If it’s something you "
"can’t do yourself, please proceed to open an issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:27 5581b1837617421f88550bf73c113647
msgid "I would like to report a security vulnerability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:30 826b929a221c4cc79315dfa426682cab
msgid ""
"Thank you! If the vulnerability is confidential, please do not report it "
"in our public issue tracker. Instead, please see :ref:`Reporting Security"
" Issues in Qubes OS <project-security/security:reporting security issues "
"in qubes os>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:33 602a2d12862641e8bf9a5b392a6a3e59
msgid "I still want to open an issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:36 3a9eaa990f9d42ac944c403803e297a0
msgid ""
"Great! Thank you for taking the time and effort to help improve Qubes! To"
" ensure the process is efficient and productive for everyone involved, "
"please follow these steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:38 a221124e3df04a30a755085ad2d7d92f
msgid ""
"Carefully read our issue tracking `guidelines <#guidelines>`__. If your "
"issue would violate any of the guidelines, **stop**. Please do not submit"
" it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:40 73fe71a33ff84be09c3cbc4c7e570224
msgid ""
"`Search through the existing issues <#search-tips>`__, both open and "
"closed, to see if your issue already exists. If it does, **stop**. "
":ref:`Do not open a duplicate. <introduction/issue-tracking:new issues "
"should not be duplicates of existing issues>` Instead, comment on the "
"existing issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:42 d5c5732511b44da6934de73ea17c327d
msgid "Go `here <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/issues/new/choose>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:44 e1c282bd2dc74092a56f1e6269d73a71
msgid "Select the `type <#types>`__ of issue you want to open."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:46 7c836acf6f064d2396689e6e64374434
msgid "Enter a descriptive title."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:48 be9adf8c7bee426aa197b3783a489551
msgid ""
"Do not delete the provided issue template. Fill out every applicable "
"section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:50 eb8695df2202458382c84c0c04977347
msgid ""
"Please note that AIs often `hallucinate "
"<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hallucination_(artificial_intelligence)>`__"
" about Qubes OS. If you're using an AI to assist you, please check its "
"conclusions against the `official documentation <https://doc.qubes-"
"os.org/>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:52 8ac055b042ed4579b91780559e2ee0a2
msgid ""
"Make sure to mention any relevant documentation and other issues you’ve "
"already seen. We don’t know what you’ve seen unless you tell us. If you "
"don’t list it, we’ll assume you haven’t seen it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:54 ce3ae7376ce8427e80524bff084b3e1d
msgid ""
"If any sections of the issue template are *truly* not applicable, you may"
" remove them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:56 a692000d66b64baa8491c29049b539e9
msgid "Submit your issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:58 94c743af9af44bd0a0a8e566f4072ca6
msgid ""
"Respond to any questions the official team asks. For example, you may be "
"asked to provide specific logs or other additional information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:62 126cec1a3d9d4b9da3922907c9e0d592
msgid ""
"Eventually, your issue may be closed. See :ref:`how issues get closed "
"<introduction/issue-tracking:how issues get closed>` for details about "
"when, why, and how this occurs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:65 68681793c82c42ae867f2c44f349c245
msgid "How issues are organized"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:68 338d91e3653d44f0a4d83fb6a9141f03
msgid ""
"Issues can have several different properties and be organized in various "
"ways. This section explains how we use labels, issue types, projects, and"
" other features of GitHub’s issue tracking system in order to keep "
"`qubes-issues <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/issues>`__ "
"organized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:71 bc9bee5c66124296a164b528c3c83237
msgid "Labels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:74 98b929198d3f4e37aa8ec8d7c9e563fd
msgid ""
"When an issue is first created, it will receive the ``P: default`` (i.e.,"
" default priority) `label <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/labels>`__ automatically. After an issue has been created, only "
"Qubes team members have permission to modify labels. Many labels have "
"descriptions on them that can be viewed by hovering over them or on the "
"`list of labels <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/labels>`__. "
"Let’s go over some of the most important ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:77 dc857d57b3c948d68143e4c8db545477
msgid "Priority"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:80 31ae9dccd4124210bb5b25ee627cbcc7
msgid ""
"There are several issue **priority** levels ranging from ``P: minor`` to "
"``P: blocker`` (see `here <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/labels?q=P%3A>`__ for the full list). Every open issue should have"
" exactly one priority. An open issue should not have more than one "
"priority, and it should not lack a priority entirely. See :ref:`here "
"<developer/releases/version-scheme:bug priorities>` for details about how"
" the developers use these priorities."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:83 05750e7260034aac918fecf0cf2251c6
msgid "Component"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:86 71e2b296af13433590c481643a02fde1
msgid ""
"There are many **component** labels, each beginning with ``C:`` (see "
"`here <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/labels?q=C%3A>`__ for the "
"full list). Every open issue should have at least one component. An open "
"issue may have more than one component, but it should not lack a "
"component entirely. When no other component applies, use ``C: other``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:89 592f9c6829ca4d3bb6bce332e6442d16
msgid "Affected release"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:92 a26315d541304ff08b3caf0ade1bd8fa
msgid ""
"A label of the form ``affects-<RELEASE_NUMBER>`` indicates that an issue "
"affects the corresponding Qubes OS release. An issue can have more than "
"one of these labels if it affects multiple releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:95 c9e8d9eab9bf46a9ad82d8f100716c76
msgid "Types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:98 78ff6981bc1d4053a30b25b526fc8986
msgid ""
"There are three issue `types <https://docs.github.com/en/issues/tracking-"
"your-work-with-issues/configuring-issues/managing-issue-types-in-an-"
"organization>`__: Bug, Feature, and Task."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:100 2b3ec75bb06b41c489ef4cc124e06ac0
msgid "**Bug** — An unexpected problem or behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:102 2d26298ed73f4b2f96d7772f4673633a
msgid "**Feature** — A request, idea, or new functionality"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:104 876b3bb4dd944a0b986ef59bf8d53c5f
msgid "**Task** — A specific piece of work"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:108 597eafa7a9b0492ab4fe77a784cc5298
msgid ""
"Every open issue should have exactly one type. **Bug** reports are for "
"problems in things that already exist. If something doesn’t exist yet, "
"but you think it ought to exist, then that issue should instead be a "
"**Feature** request. If something already exists, but you think it could "
"be improved in some way, that also qualifies as a **Feature** request. "
"The **Task** type is for issues that are actionable but that fall under "
"neither the **Bug** nor **Feature** types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:111 1099e624407249b083e3bb5e8e6e9fa4
msgid "Projects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:114 ad94ad1e07864628a00c2dac059136e9
msgid ""
"According to GitHub, a `project <https://docs.github.com/en/issues"
"/planning-and-tracking-with-projects/learning-about-projects/about-"
"projects>`__ is “an adaptable spreadsheet, task-board, and road map that "
"integrates with your issues and pull requests on GitHub to help you plan "
"and track your work effectively.” The issue tracker has several `projects"
" <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/projects>`__. Github projects "
"allows more detailed issue states, and also attaching more metadata to "
"issues. They also allow more focused view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:116 b9feec6bebe841b3ae62e73aaee879ae
msgid ""
"There is a special project in Qubes OS project: the `Current team tasks "
"project <https://github.com/orgs/QubesOS/projects/19/views/1>`__ which "
"represents current work of the core team. Issues in this project’s "
"**backlog** section are not yet ready for work - they might be waiting "
"for clarifications, blockers, decisions on priorities etc. Issues that "
"are **ready** can be picked up by any team member. There should not be "
"too many issues in **ready** column to decrease confusion and decision "
"paralysis - good number is around 20. The **in review** state means that "
"the developer is finished with the work (the completion state has been "
"reached) - if something has to be postponed or abandoned, a justification"
" should be posted in issue discussion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:119 33a856f12c7041559a7b988cce54192e
msgid "Meta-issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:122 a6bab2be2d294ad6951f5904f7e59692
msgid ""
"A meta-issue is an issue that serves primarily to collect and organize a "
"group of other issues. This group of other issues typically exists in a "
"hierarchy of `sub-issues <https://docs.github.com/en/issues/tracking-"
"your-work-with-issues/using-issues/adding-sub-issues>`__, usually with "
"the meta-issue at the top. (For example, we use meta-issues when we need "
"a way to track work on specific features. We cannot use `projects "
"<#projects>`__ for this, because we already use a project for tracking "
"the work of the Qubes team as a whole, and projects cannot contain "
"milestones or other projects.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:124 8a65c877bee2477f96cbf3874fb0aa6b
msgid ""
"Meta-issues should have informative descriptions, not just lists of "
"issues. In particular, each meta-issue should explain its goal, what is "
"in scope, and what the relevant categories and priorities are."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:126 68957ac48d34423d9d09e95f11380ba3
msgid ""
"In addition, meta-issues should have clear, concrete, and actionable "
"criteria for when they will be closed. Meta-issues should never be “open-"
"ended” or expected to stay open indefinitely. If this ever becomes "
"unclear, the meta-issue should be closed until it becomes clear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:129 346a9820af274cf19179195471fbff96
msgid "Search tips"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:132 40a588e6d36b413393b3201906c1c777
#, python-format
msgid ""
"`Search both open and closed issues. <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue>`__ For example, you may be "
"experiencing a bug that was just fixed, in which case the report for that"
" bug is probably closed. In this case, it would be useful to view `all "
"bug reports, both open and closed, with the most recently updated sorted "
"to the top <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues?q=label%3A%22T%3A+bug%22+sort%3Aupdated-desc>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:134 866ea360f652436391478b3205c1851a
#, python-format
msgid ""
"`Search with labels. <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/labels>`__ "
"For example, you can search issues by priority (`blocker "
"<https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/labels/P%3A%20blocker>`__, "
"`critical <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/labels/P%3A%20critical>`__, `major <https://github.com/QubesOS"
"/qubes-issues/labels/P%3A%20major>`__, etc.) and by component (`core "
"<https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues?q=is%3Aopen+is%3Aissue+label%3A%22C%3A+core%22>`__, "
"`manager/widget <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aopen+is%3Aissue+label%3A%22C%3A+manager%2Fwidget%22+>`__,"
" `Xen <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues?q=is%3Aopen+is%3Aissue+label%3A%22C%3A+Xen%22>`__, etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:136 e8079910b75c4abf9c1159b9c2b58390
msgid ""
"Search by closure reason: `reason:completed <https://github.com/QubesOS"
"/qubes-issues/issues?q=reason%3Acompleted>`__ and `reason:\"not planned\""
" <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues?q=reason%3A%22not+planned%22>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:138 e22120f13b564a81b4fc2f35f4925e03
msgid "`Search by project <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/projects>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:143 2b0dbc64c8f64a5db6e645c192d1b5c6
msgid "Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:147 05bca17c4c6c43cb842ea80014bd9012
msgid "The issue tracker is not a discussion forum"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:150 79aaf7f8e8f74f7ca131c9f2ac756d7d
msgid ""
"The issue tracker is a tool to help the developers be more productive and"
" efficient in their work. It is not a place for discussion. If you wish "
"to discuss something in the issue tracker, please do so on the forum or "
"mailing lists (see :doc:`Help, Support, Mailing Lists, and Forum "
"</introduction/support>`). You can simply link to the relevant issue in "
"your discussion post."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:152 5537f2b78e8c4f1bad04e5dc574dad16
msgid ""
"This guideline is important for keeping issues focused on *actionable "
"information*, which helps the developers to stay focused on their work. "
"When developers come back to an issue to work on it, we do not want them "
"to have to sift through a large number of unnecessary comments before "
"they can get started. In many cases, an issue that gets “too big” "
"essentially becomes more trouble than it’s worth, and no developer will "
"touch it (also see `every issue must be about a single, actionable thing "
"<#every-issue-must-be-about-a-single-actionable-thing>`__). In these "
"cases, we sometimes have to close the issue and open a new one. This is a"
" waste of energy for everyone involved, so we ask that everyone help to "
"avoid repeating this pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:155 a166fec123e244e48e6aa077328e3445
msgid "Do not submit questions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:158 086e0bfd55204216ab1648861ff32677
msgid ""
"`qubes-issues <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/issues>`__ is not "
"the place to ask questions. This includes, but is not limited to, "
"troubleshooting questions and questions about how to do things with "
"Qubes. Instead, see :doc:`Help, Support, Mailing Lists, and Forum "
"</introduction/support>` for appropriate places to ask questions. By "
"contrast, `qubes-issues <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues>`__ is meant for tracking more general bugs, enhancements, "
"and tasks that affect a broad range of Qubes users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:161 dce10ac90352401c97b32aa83b50a103
msgid "Use the issue template"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:164 de98e24307954ef1b695134de44af197
msgid ""
"When you open a new issue, an issue template is provided for you. Please "
"use it. Do not delete it. The issue template is carefully designed to "
"elicit important information. Without this information, the issue is "
"likely to be incomplete. (If certain sections are not applicable, you may"
" remove them, but please do so only sparingly and only if they are "
"*truly* not applicable.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:166 171ca6f502564253a85a7f1f3cfa3a0b
msgid ""
"It is also important to note the placement and content of the HTML "
"comments in the issue template. These help us to have issues with a "
"consistent format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:169 8f5b4b07db0d402a8b1ea539c2ae1014
msgid "Every issue must be about a single, actionable thing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:172 7303d12358f44b0dacea3ef78bf38b9c
msgid ""
"If your issue is not actionable, please see :doc:`Help, Support, Mailing "
"Lists, and Forum </introduction/support>` for the appropriate place to "
"post it. If your issue would be about more than one thing, file them as "
"separate issues instead. This means we should generally not try to use a "
"single issue as a “meta” or “epic” issue that exists only to group, "
"contain, or track other issues. Instead, when there is a need to group "
"multiple related issues together, use `projects "
"<https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/projects>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:174 1fb989e209794df6a2a6354c494a4058
msgid ""
"This guideline is extremely important for making the issue tracker a "
"useful tool for the developers. When an issue is too big and composite, "
"it becomes intractable and drastically increases the likelihood that "
"nothing will get done. Such issues also tend to encourage an excessive "
"amount of general discussion that is simply not appropriate for a "
"technical issue tracker (see `the issue tracker is not a discussion forum"
" <#the-issue-tracker-is-not-a-discussion-forum>`__)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:177 e45f0b456c8b483499dea0092427d3e4
msgid "Every issue must be of a single type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:180 cf8f19b622f84f0d98f7456254ca469b
msgid ""
"Every issue must be exactly one of the following types: a bug report "
"(``bug``), a feature or improvement request (``enhancement``), or a task "
"(``task``). Do not file multi-typed issues. Instead, file multiple issues"
" of distinct types. The Qubes team will classify your issue according to "
"its type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:183 d66d6101e40c4fc689143f517ba693bc
msgid "New issues should not be duplicates of existing issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:186 80d7c267c01545f1bb17fec38d4047c1
msgid ""
"Before you submit an issue, check to see whether it has already been "
"reported. Search through the existing issues – both open and closed – by "
"typing your key words in the **Filters** box. If you find an issue that "
"seems to be similar to yours, read through it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:188 995e272668de45acac2410a7499b934b
msgid ""
"For bug reports, if you find an issue that is the same as or subsumes "
"yours, leave a comment on the existing bug report issue rather than "
"opening a new one, even if the existing bug report is closed. If a bug "
"report affects more than one Qubes version, we usually keep only one bug "
"report for all versions. The Qubes team will see your comment and reopen "
"the bug report, if appropriate. For example, you can leave a comment with"
" additional information to help the maintainer debug it. Adding a comment"
" will subscribe you to email notifications, which can be helpful in "
"getting important updates regarding the issue. If you don’t have anything"
" to add but still want to receive email updates, you can click the "
"“Subscribe” button at the side or bottom of the comments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:190 82a130718a594d14bc9114ccd2eb9fc9
msgid ""
"For feature requests, it depends on what you want to report. If the "
"initial implementation was incomplete or unsuccessful, then please leave "
"a comment on the existing feature request issue, and we will reopen it. "
"However, if the initial implementation of the feature was successful, and"
" you are reporting a problem with the feature that arose later, then "
"please open a separate bug report (if one doesn't already exist for that "
"bug) instead of commenting on the old feature request, as we generally "
"prefer not to reopen old feature requests the initial implemntation of "
"which was successfully completed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:194 12a71efbaffb423d88086926456f9805
msgid "New issues should include all relevant information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:197 f47b18492ef7419b8cc3812d35f034ea
msgid ""
"When you file a new issue, you should be sure to include the version of "
"Qubes you’re using, as well as versions of related software packages "
"(:doc:`how to copy information out of dom0 </user/how-to-guides/how-to-"
"copy-from-dom0>`). If your issue is related to hardware, provide as many "
"details as possible about the hardware. A great way to do this is by "
":ref:`generating and submitting a Hardware Compatibility List (HCL) "
"report <user/hardware/how-to-use-the-hcl:generating and submitting new "
"reports>`, then linking to it in your issue. You may also need to use "
"command-line tools such as ``lspci``. If you’re reporting a bug in a "
"package that is in a :doc:`testing </user/downloading-installing-"
"upgrading/testing>` repository, please reference the appropriate issue in"
" the `updates-status <https://github.com/QubesOS/updates-"
"status/issues>`__ repository. Project maintainers really appreciate "
"thorough explanations. It usually helps them address the problem more "
"quickly, so everyone wins!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:200 e11d2f20d3ae4f478b27988a0330acfd
msgid "There are no guarantees that your issue will be addressed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:203 4c7e9e099bd5449d90f209f87748e672
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that `qubes-issues <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues>`__ is an issue tracker, not a support system. Creating a "
"new issue is simply a way for you to submit an item for the Qubes team’s "
"consideration. It is up to the Qubes team to decide whether or how to "
"address your issue, which may include closing the issue without taking "
"any action on it. Even if your issue is kept open, however, you should "
"not expect it to be addressed within any particular time frame, or at "
"all. At the time of this writing, there are well over one thousand open "
"issues in `qubes-issues <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-"
"issues/issues>`__. The Qubes team has its own roadmap and priorities, "
"which will govern the manner and order in which open issues are "
"addressed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:206 8f67ed46eb724f2183f2c7283ce16cb4
msgid "Issues and comments must be written in English"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:209 67e6e120a5404401a1bda0de628e2fca
msgid ""
"If English is not your native language, you may post a machine "
"translation. If you wish, you may also include the original non-English "
"text in a `collapsible section <#use-collapsible-sections-for-long-"
"nonessential-content>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:212 625b6dd6fc9440d582041e7ad2b08bef
msgid "Use collapsible sections for long, nonessential content"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:215 1bd2f2e730b24a12bbda5738a3fd2691
msgid "On GitHub, create collapsible sections in Markdown like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:228 484f570ebd594effb9e84be0bdbe4749
msgid ""
"**Tip:** Use the “Preview” tab to make sure it renders correctly before "
"posting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:231 cd98e3a5a70a4ba3a4fa2f8e9a2235d9
msgid "How issues get closed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:234 5a5ed5196ba54fd7b7f661b5a3641d3a
msgid ""
"If the Qubes developers make a code change that resolves an issue, then "
"the issue will typically be `closed from the relevant commit or merged "
"pull request (PR) <https://docs.github.com/en/issues/tracking-your-work-"
"with-issues/creating-issues/linking-a-pull-request-to-an-issue>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:237 6f214afedc46421dbb5a586c9ffac8ab
msgid "Bug reports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:240 91fa8ef2636649e6ab7a14207b65242d
msgid ""
"In the case of bugs, the package containing the change will move to the "
"appropriate :doc:`testing </user/downloading-installing-"
"upgrading/testing>` repository, then to the appropriate stable "
"repository. If you so choose, you can test the fix while it’s in the "
":doc:`testing </user/downloading-installing-upgrading/testing>` "
"repository, or you can wait for it to land in the stable repository. If, "
"after testing the fix, you find that it does not really fix the reported "
"bug, please leave a comment on the issue explaining the situation. When "
"you do, we will receive a notification and respond on the issue or reopen"
" it (or both). Please **do not** create a duplicate issue or attempt to "
"contact the developers individually about a problem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:243 26289222e8bb423994df0ca83976b875
msgid "Resolution"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:246 3a658f2f2d0742a4a8655c6abb88ad0a
#, python-format
msgid ""
"In GitHub, an issue can be `closed as either \"completed\" or \"not "
"planned\" <https://github.blog/changelog/2022-03-10-the-new-github-"
"issues-march-10th-update/#%F0%9F%95%B5%F0%9F%8F%BD%E2%99%80%EF%B8%8F-"
"issue-closed-reasons>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:248 2f24cae419884be788790bfb86540d6d
msgid ""
"Being closed as ``completed`` means that the issue has been fixed (in the"
" case of bugs) or done (in the case of enhancements and tasks). More "
"precisely, it means that a commit containing the relevant work has been "
"pushed. It takes time for this work to make its way into a package, which"
" must then go through the :doc:`testing </user/downloading-installing-"
"upgrading/testing>` process before finally landing in the relevant stable"
" repository. Automated comments on the issue will announce when key "
"events in this process occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:250 49ad9d6edca044cba718c5db8fd74165
msgid ""
"Being closed as ``not planned`` means that the issue will *not* be fixed "
"(in the case of bugs) or done (in the case of enhancements and tasks). "
"When an issue is closed as ``not planned``, we add a **resolution** label"
" starting with ``R:`` that specifies the reason for the closure, such as "
"``R: duplicate`` or ``R: cannot reproduce``. Each of these labels has a "
"description that briefly explains the label. We also leave a comment "
"containing a longer explanation for why the issue is being closed along "
"with general information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:252 f556173e69514fec9befc13a5bea6523
msgid ""
"While issues that are closed as ``not planned`` get a more specific "
"resolution label, issues that are closed as ``completed`` do not always "
"get one, since the linked PRs, commits, automated messages, and the "
"``completed`` reason itself are often sufficient to convey all relevant "
"information. For information about using closure reasons in searches, see"
" `Search tips <#search-tips>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:255 5c799163d39048649a7deb95d74a1d82
msgid "Backports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:258 8f8c38a51e7848d2a1680153979ea497
msgid ""
"Issues in GitHub can only be open or closed, but when it comes to bugs "
"that affect multiple versions of Qubes OS, there are several possible "
"states:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:260 aeb2f30dbf07466b87de016088e3a5f8
msgid "Not fixed yet"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:262 715d88d21a864b73ad9d60f726facdc5
msgid "Fix developed but not yet committed (PR open)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:264 578ce5617f95454b9b07e603be59ca3b
msgid "Fix committed (PR merged), but update not yet pushed to any repo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:266 243e326bd64c496187deefd4309dec69
msgid "Update pushed to testing repo for the most recent development version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:268 28e2c941b7d342e4af96436f48307696
msgid "Update pushed to stable repo for the most recent development version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:270 a0fc76ffbaa04b7c9309bb22c53af022
msgid "Update backported to stable version(s) and pushed to the testing repo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:272 03d341b94df74706a4e55556719ba3ab
msgid "Update pushed to stable repo of stable version(s)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:276 1feaded8adcc4330951884cda4280d8c
msgid ""
"We close issues at step 3. Then, as updates are released, the issue "
"automatically gets the appropriate ``current-testing`` (``rX.Y-*-cur-"
"test``) and ``stable`` (``rX.Y-*-stable``) labels. Based on these labels,"
" it’s possible to select issues waiting for step 6 (see `issues by "
"release <https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues#issues-by-release>`__)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:278 d541d7c4fd774bd5adee5fea8288463d
msgid ""
"Therefore, if you see that an issue is closed, but the fix is not yet "
"available to you, be aware that it may be at an intermediate stage of "
"this process between issue closure and the update being available in "
"whichever repos you have enabled in whichever version of Qubes you’re "
"using."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:280 e37fb9339e654d1d884e9830e553d3c3
msgid ""
"In order to assist with this, we have a label called `backport pending "
"<https://github.com/QubesOS/qubes-issues/labels/backport%20pending>`__, "
"which means, “The fix has been released for the testing release but is "
"pending backport to the stable release.” Our infrastructure will attempt "
"to apply this label automatically, when appropriate, but it is not "
"perfect, and the developers may need to adjust it manually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:283 952e53b01f624613be9c0049f1fca768
msgid "Understanding open and closed issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:286 768ef3a903854a1ebafb297ba704f53e
msgid ""
"Every issue is always in one of two states: open or closed, with open "
"being the default. The **open** and **closed** states mean that, "
"according to our available information at present, the issue in question "
"either **is** or **is not** (respectively) actionable for the Qubes team."
" The open and closed states do not mean anything more than this, and it’s"
" important not to read anything else into them. It’s also important to "
"understand that closing an issue is, in effect, nothing more than "
"changing a virtual tag on an issue. Closing an issue is never “final” in "
"any sense, and it does not affect the issue itself in any other way. "
"Issues can be opened and closed instantly with a single button press an "
"unlimited number of times at no cost. In fact, since the open and closed "
"states reflect our available information at present, one should expect "
"these states to change back and forth as new information becomes "
"available. Closed issues are fully searchable, just like open issues, and"
" we explicitly instruct all users of the issue tracker to search *both* "
"open *and* closed issues, which GitHub makes easy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:289 59b6698e0c1148268540bd7915e08308
msgid "Workflow and what do issue states mean"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:292 ed855d0749394eeabc989100d938baee
msgid "There are some rules we use when assigning issues and tagging them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:295 9b331f529da44d3ba36b9fd177533f6b
msgid "Assigning issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:298 3060343f6b3742f39fa88819a007b67f
msgid ""
"To avoid a situation where an issue is “dead” - assigned to someone who "
"is not actively working on it - and to help the team organize their work,"
" an issue should be assigned to a person who currently works on it, or "
"will start working on it in a very near future (about a week or two). One"
" person can have several issues assigned at the same time (for example "
"they may be working on one another issue while waiting for review), but "
"if an issue is no longer actively being worked on (for example when it’s "
"blocked by something else), it should be unassigned. At that point, if "
"there is some partial work already done, there should be a comment about "
"that, including link to the code (some WIP commit in some branch?) if "
"applicable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:300 87c3f982a3dd47fd81043fdfdb8dd7f4
msgid ""
"Issues should not be assigned as a todo-list several months in the "
"future, or assigned to someone without their explicit confirmation that "
"they are currently working on that issue or will start doing it shortly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:303 5b39403e0384481480037ade8208a60e
msgid "Working on an issue"
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:306 1da13a17baef479ab91fd116ebb9d666
msgid ""
"Every issue should involve a clear statement of success: when is the "
"issue finished? It might not be clear to the person making the issue, "
"especially if it’s an enhancement request, but before work starts, the "
"person working on the issue should make sure that it includes clear "
"completion criteria in the description (via editing the description, if "
"necessary). The completion criteria would ideally be a checklist, and "
"consist of a list of pull requests/features, each preferably no more than"
" two weeks of work. It’s also important to remember tests and "
"documentation should also be part of the issue, if applicable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:308 056f548bf0d0448cb2da019670b3a2b9
msgid ""
"An issue should also have a rough estimate how much time it needs, if "
"it’s more than one-two days. Of course this might be updated later, if an"
" issue turns out to be more (or maybe less) complicated than it has "
"initially seemed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../introduction/issue-tracking.rst:310 518f1e239aff403c8718ab9472308acc
msgid ""
"When an issue is done (that is, the completion checklist has been "
"completed), the issue should be moved to **ready** column in the *Current"
" team tasks* project."
msgstr ""

